$ cat FILE_NAME                                                         # view a single file
$ cat FILE_NAME FILE_NAME                                               # view multiple files
$ cat ~/.FOLDER_NAME/FILE_NAME
  cat ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
$ cat FILE_NAME FILE_NAME FILE_NAME > FILE_NAME                         # multiple files into one single file using the “>”
$ cat FILE_NAME > /FOLDER_NAME/FILE_NAME                                 
$ cat FILE_NAME >> FILE_NAME                                            # appending file into another existing file
$ cat FILE_NAME >> ~/.FOLDER_NAME/FILE_NAME
  cat id_rsa.pub >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys
$ cat > FILE_NAME                                                       # creating a file with text, Ctrl+d - save & exit, “>” - 1st time & overwrite
$ cat >> FILE_NAME                                                      # appending text into existing file, Ctrl+d - save & exit
$ cat -n FILE_NAME                                                      # display including empty lines  
$ cat -b FILE_NAME                                                      # display only the number of each non-empty line

cat & grep with pipe - The 'cat & grep' command is generally used with pipe (|).

$ cat FILE_NAME | grep NO
$ cat FILE_NAME | grep WORD_NAME
$ cat FILE_NAME | grep LETTER
